<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-26_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-27_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-28_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions and regulations
</h3><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-30_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span><strong>First aid</strong> - The immediate assistance given to any person suffering from either a minor or serious illness or injury, with care provided to preserve life, prevent the condition from worsening, or to promote recovery.<br>







<br>In terms of regulatory frameworks, organisations such as the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) in the UK suggest that childcare providers should have at least one person trained in paediatric first aid present during operating hours. The Care Quality Commission (CQC) further supports these standards, advocating for rigorous first aid training and preparedness.
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-32_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-33_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-34_ pf-heading-1-h3">Managing splinters - Best practices</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-36_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Initial assessment</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-38_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-39_ pf-text-1"><strong>Calm and reassure</strong> - Keeping the child calm is crucial, as distress can complicate the removal process.










</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-41_ pf-text-1"><strong>Examine</strong> -&nbsp;Carefully inspect the type and depth of the splinter before attempting removal.
















</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-43_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Safe removal</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-45_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-46_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clean </strong>- Wash your hands and the affected area with soap and water to prevent infection.











</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-48_ pf-text-1"><strong>Tools</strong> - Use sterilised tweezers and a needle. Sterilise by wiping it with an alcohol wipe or boiling it for a few minutes.


















</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-50_ pf-text-1"><strong>Technique</strong> - Gently pull the splinter at the same angle it entered. For deep splinters, a sterilised needle may be used to gently tease the skin layer covering the splinter.


















</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-52_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Post-removal care</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-54_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-55_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clean and protect</strong> -&nbsp;After removal, remove the area and apply a mild antiseptic.












</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-57_ pf-text-1"><strong>Monitor</strong> - Watch for signs of infection such as redness, swelling, or pus.













